body.plain: UK singer song writer, Cleo Sol’s single, “Why Don’t You” , which is lifted from her debut EP titled Winter Songs.

annotations: In this Verse Cleo acknowledges her flaws but then talks how she has grown and is still growing as a human being and bettering herself

I’m not perfect
 So I try everyday and I grow a little bit
 Read a little more so I can educate my kids
 Reap for my soul and cleanse my spirit
 Pray cause I’m ready for the bloom of the sea
 Peace and serenity is all that I need
She starts by accepting the fact she’s not perfect because no one is. She then talks about trying to grow as a person by naming multiple ways she has promoted her self growth

Sometimes I still doubt myself
 But at least now I love myself
Cleo is saying that she’s grown as a person and now loves herself although she doubts herself at times

You wanna help your friends
 But trust me baby
 You don’t owe them
 Don’t take on peoples problems

This one needs a little unpacking and may seem like a stretch once explained at first read, but in the conditions are right, I’m right.

I assume the friends she use to hang around were also troubled people just like her or the man she’s speaking to (if so).

People with personality disorders tend to flock together (but constantly interchanging). Cleo or the man she’s speaking to works real hard to obtain self-love and wants to help their friends but because personality disorders are almost impossible to correct, she’s telling herself/him “You don’t owe them; Don’t take on people’s problems”.

I know you can’t relax
 And you don’t want me to know that

People with Borderline feel intense feelings and for a longer time. The average person feels feelings on a slow curve. Borderlines feel intense emotions sooner and for a longer time. Their brains have not developed proper emotional regulation skills. Hence the line “I know you can’t relax”.

Don’t complain about finance
 I know your daddy weren’t a real man

(Issues with childhood especially in the father department)

I don’t know anything about Cleo’s personal life but it I had to make an educated guess while using this particular line, I’d say she or the man she may be speaking to didn’t have a grate childhood.

According to a Cambridge University study in 2002,  “Child abuse and neglect have repeatedly been shown to be risks for psychiatric and personality disorders.” …[they] report mental disorders assessed from early childhood to adulthood in those later identified as victims of abuse or neglect by official or self-report.” (Cohen, Brown, & Smailes, 2001)

This line to me translates to: Don’t complain about money like your father did.

Why don’t you just let go
 And quiet down your ego

When you first listen to the song, you may be inclined to believe she is only speaking to someone else. Cleo is also speaking to herself and about her mental health.

A core part of Cluster B Borderline Personality Disorder is egoism. People with this kind of personality disorder have a grandiose image of themselves and can be quite much to handle.
